A person who is assigned male at birth who dresses in a traditionally feminine manner within a given sociocultural context.
Note that a transgender woman may cross-dress "male-to-female" before transitioning, but this does not make that person a male-to-female cross-dresser.

Name given to certain performers in American circus sideshow and carnival circuits during the first half of the 20th century. These performers would often claim to be "true hermaphrodites" (intersex individuals), presenting as male on one side of their body and female on the other side of their body. Well-known "half-and-half" performers included Josephine Joseph and Bobby Kork.
An entertainer who cross-dresses  for the purposes of entertainment.
It is important to note that gender impersonation is usually considered separate from the concept of drag.
A male entertainer who dresses as female for the purposes of entertainment.

Early female impersonators may have been recognized as transgender today. The practice also overlaps significantly with drag, specifically the conceptualization of drag queens, but these two practices are generally not considered synonymous.
A female entertainer who dresses as male for the purposes of entertainment.

Early male impersonators may have been recognized as transgender today. The practice also overlaps significantly with drag, specifically the conceptualization of drag kings, but these two practices are generally not considered synonymous.
A primarily performative cultural identity in many Spanish and Portuguese speaking countries in Central and South America.
"Transformista" is often translated as "transvestite" in English, which is an inaccurate translation. While "transformist" may be more appropriate, using "transformista" is usually preferred.

The transformista identity predates the emergence of the  American "drag queen" identity in many Central and South American countries. Their performances usually involve specific impersonation of Central and South American "divas" as well as dance and music specific to those cultures.

An act in which an entertainer who dresses stereotypically, exaggeratedly, or otherwise provocatively as a person of a different gender (usually men as women or women as men, as perceived in a particular culture and time period), often accompanied by song in some form or fashion. Early gender impersonators may have been recognized as transgender today. The practice also overlaps significantly with drag, but these two practices are generally not considered synonymous.

An act in which a female entertainer who dresses stereotypically, exaggeratedly, or otherwise provocatively as a man, often accompanied by song in some form or fashion. Early male impersonators may have been recognized as transgender today. The practice also overlaps significantly with drag, specifically the conceptualization of drag kings, but these two practices are generally not considered synonymous.
